<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910724-0017</DOCNO><DOCID>910724-0017.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>07/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   BCCI'S ALLEGED FRAUD reaches to the top of the bankingcompany, including board members representing its Abu Dhabishare holders, according to the Bank of England. The Britishcentral bank's governor linked the scandal to the palace ofAbu Dhabi's ruler, who has insisted that all of the allegedfraud occurred before he gained control.   ---</LP><TEXT>   Unisys plans to cut 10,000 jobs and took a $1.2 billioncharge, resulting in a $1.3 billion quarterly loss. Thelatest results bring the computer and defense-electronicscompany's losses to $2.5 billion over the past 2 1/2 years.   ---   Stocks fell on a sagging bond market and disappointingearnings news. The Dow Jones industrials lost 29.74 to2983.23. The dollar declined.   ---   Earnings at 3M in the second quarter fell 13%, and themanufacturing company indicated its second-half results willtrail year-earlier levels.   ---   Mobil and Phillips Petroleum posted declines insecond-quarter net. But Occidental's earnings jumped 65%, asign that its restructuring is paying off, the company said.   ---   McDonnell Douglas faced such serious cash flow problemsearly this year that it asked the Pentagon for a $1 billionadvance on contracts. The contractor withdrew the requestwhen its prospects improved.   ---   Salomon, Morgan Stanley and Alex. Brown posted sharpincreases in second-quarter net, getting boosts from highertrading profits and in creased underwriting activity.   ---   Digital Equipment intends to purchase a loss-makingcomputer business from Dutch electronics concern Philips. Theoperation had revenue of about $1 billion last year.   ---   A banking-bill proposal that would cap the interest ratepaid on federally insured deposits is drawing renewedinterest from Democrats. But the plan still faces majorobstacles.   ---   Germany's Daimler-Benz agreed to pay over $568 million foran indirect 34% stake in French computer-services company CapGemini.   ---   UAL's United Airlines sweetened its offer for Pan Am'sLatin American routes to $235 million, according to a personfamiliar with the talks.   ---   Japan's Itoman trading concern said three ex-officialswere arrested after a probe into alleged fraud in art, realestate and stock trades.   ---   An employer at an impasse in bargaining with its union canlegally put a merit-raise proposal into effect withoutobtaining the union's agreement, a U.S. appeals court ruled.   ---   Monsanto posted a quarterly loss of $52 million after arestructuring charge. But strength in agricultural andchemicals areas helped the company beat analysts'expectations.   ---   Tokyo stocks snapped a five-day losing streak, receiving aboost from index-linked buying. The Nikkei index climbed53.69 to 22758.98.   ---   Canada's First City Financial made a debt restructuringproposal to bondholders that could see the Belzberg family'scontrol of the company fall to about 24% from 80%.   ---   South Korea is setting a &quot;minimum import price&quot; on aplastic resin sold by three foreign chemical makers, whichwere found to be dumping the product in Korea.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 160,010,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2983.23, off 29.74; transportation 1202.40, off 9.87;utilities 200.26, off 0.38.   Bonds: Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3761.43, off 6.07.   Commodities: Oil $21.32 a barrel, off 55 cents. Dow Jonesfutures index 123.47, up 0.45; spot index 123.52, up 0.45.   Dollar: 137.24 yen, off 0.41; 1.7575 marks, off 0.0045.</TEXT></DOC>